<h2>The ICU Experience Requirement: What Actually Qualifies</h2>

<p>The most misunderstood CRNA admission requirement is ICU experience. The key points:</p>

<p><strong>Must be adult ICU:</strong> The requirement is "adult critical care experience." PICU, NICU, and pediatric-only ICU experience does not satisfy this requirement at most CRNA programs. Nurses from these backgrounds typically need to transition to an adult ICU and build the required hours there.</p>

<p><strong>Must be direct patient care:</strong> Charge nurse, manager, or educator roles that don't involve direct bedside ICU care do not count. The requirement is bedside ICU nursing — hands on patients.</p>

<p><strong>Hours calculation:</strong> Most programs specify "1 year" which typically means 12 months of full-time (0.9–1.0 FTE) employment in the ICU. Part-time ICU hours may not satisfy the full-time-equivalent requirement at some programs — verify per program.</p>

<p><strong>Type of ICU matters for competitiveness (not minimum qualification):</strong> Any accredited adult ICU satisfies the minimum requirement. CTICU, CVICU, or MICU at a high-volume academic medical center makes you more competitive. A low-acuity community hospital ICU with limited vasoactive management and rare intubations meets the technical requirement but may leave gaps in clinical preparation that emerge in interviews.</p>

