<h2>The DNP Requirement: What Changed in 2025</h2>

<p>Since 2025, all CRNA programs are required to award the Doctor of Nursing Practice (DNP) rather than the Master of Science in Nursing (MSN). This means all CRNA graduates are now doctoral-level providers. Program lengths have extended accordingly — most are now 28–36 months, with some integrated BSN-to-DNP tracks available for nurses planning far in advance.</p>

<p>The DNP degree requirement does not increase the admission requirements — the same ICU experience, GPA, and clinical criteria apply. It does mean a longer time in school and more tuition cost than the historical MSN-CRNA programs. The income return remains strongly positive: CRNA salaries ($200,000–$250,000 average) support comfortable loan repayment on most program tuition levels.</p>

